#week-title("Four", "Designing the Post-Curriculum Practice")

=== Core Teaching

Month 8, Week 4 asks the Adept to look beyond the curriculum — to the shape of
the alchemical practice that will continue after the structured three-year
framework ends.

The curriculum ends at Year Three Month 12. The Work does not. The preparations
underway will continue. The journals will continue. The daily laboratory visits
will continue. What changes at Month 12 is not the Work but the container: the
curriculum's monthly structure, its assigned readings, its quarterly gatherings,
its headmaster and guide support in its formal mode.

*What to carry forward.* The Adept who approaches this question honestly will
find that not everything in the curriculum was equally important for them.
Some threads caught fire and deepened across the three years; others remained
formal obligations that never came fully alive. The post-curriculum practice
should:

1. *Continue the active preparations* that are genuinely underway — the
   circulation, the Via Humida mineral work, and any other sealed works.
   These cannot be stopped at Month 12 without consequences; they continue at
   their own pace.
2. *Maintain the journal discipline* — both laboratory and inner work — as
   the practitioner's primary instrument of discernment and longitudinal record.
3. *Identify two or three source texts* to continue working with as primary
   references after the curriculum readings are concluded. Which texts have
   proven most directly useful? Which are clearly not yet exhausted?
4. *Sustain one inner practice* at minimum — the sustained practice declared
   in Year Two Month 9. If that practice has been maintained, it is already
   post-curriculum ready.
5. *Maintain connection with the community* — whether through the academy's
   ongoing gatherings, through correspondence with the headmaster or guide, or
   through independent study circles.

=== Topics This Week

- Identifying the threads that caught fire vs. the formal obligations
- The five elements of the post-curriculum practice
- Choosing the two or three source texts to carry forward
- The community as a sustaining structure beyond the formal curriculum

